    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-18T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-18T06:00:00-05:00" n="479"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d479">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/224</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-18T11:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 18, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.08 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9088. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1"
                        >Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 295. Referring my 290. As regards the suggestion that Dutch public opinion
                    would be placated if embargo could be lifted on quarter’s rations of few
                    commodities, <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName>
                    informs me that he considers this suggestion inadvisable believing that so long
                    as the Dutch want to get something out of us they are not so likely to quarrel
                    with us and if we should give them commodities which might tend even in a small
                    measure to render them independent of us, they might be more abusive of the
                    Allies than otherwise. He finishes his letter by stating that he rather regrets
                    the generosity of the United States in promising straight away 100,000 tons of
                    grain and says that he would feel reluctant to go beyond that.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
